<subSubSection id="E0FBEF5D361D2B59DE03A6F89F131AEE" pageId="2" pageNumber="69" type="holotype ♀">
<paragraph id="06C3FCCC91CB6EFC6442C724E2A70250" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Holotype ♀:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="690E5E96A9F7C0DFD1277CFCB3001E26" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">
COLOMBIA, Valle del Cauca, PNN Farallones de Cali, Anchicaya, 
<geoCoordinate id="6C06D3C3D5EB4A5702DDC7247FCE68E2" degrees="3" direction="south" minutes="26" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-3.4333334">3°26'S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="E6456FC2DCEAB020DC7FAD11A1D2C82C" degrees="76" direction="west" minutes="48" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-76.8">76°48'W</geoCoordinate>
, 900 m, Malaise trap, 1 August - 10 October 2000, leg. S. Sarria. - Holotype is in good condition: (1) glued on a card point by its right mesopleuron, (2) right antenna broken, with 15 antennomeres, (3) right fore wing creased apico-posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2C01971EF97DC24F83CB720EC0ACAF00" pageId="2" pageNumber="69" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="ADC608BF39D195ACEDBB32AA1B81520E" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="35BF8F8AF5DEE766B0DFFD56A5786EF9" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">
The new species is named after the type locality, 
<normalizedToken id="0E19E20C763F4F933345AA143B427BDE" originalValue="”Cauca”">&quot;Cauca&quot;</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A18C53C94E65ED8858696D9A907AA64B" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="70" pageId="2" pageNumber="69" type="description">
<paragraph id="6FBAD460F45829E4EDC40E4E14A6979B" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2A595E6C75551538722C042D4B4B71A" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">
Body 2.6 mm long. Antenna as long as body and with 21 antennomeres. First flagellomere three times as long as broad apically, further flagellomeres gradually shortening and indistinctly attenuating so that penultimate flagellomere 2.5 times as long as broad. Head in dorsal view less transverse or subcubic (
<figureCitation id="07C5306F6D7788916C962A3F21F5E86A" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), 1.7 times as broad as long, eye almost 2.9 times as long as temple, temple rounded. Ocelli medium-sized, OOL almost three times as long as POL. Eye in lateral view nearly 1.5 times as high as wide and nearly 1.6 times as wide as temple, temple beyond eye evenly widened (
<figureCitation id="2025F6B9340F03DB2A8D3CAE969A5479" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
, see arrows). Lower tooth of mandible somewhat small, mandible twice as long as broad between upper and lower teeth (
<figureCitation id="7D0D6A882916D1B522D52052E1361F80" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Paraclypeal pit short, i.e. distance between pit and eye as long as length of paraclypeal pit itself (
<figureCitation id="A218934FC56A7C876F859CD848AA7B5C" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Maxillary palp one-sixth longer than height of head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="243E1582B0283A01357A213363F211DB" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="70" pageId="2" pageNumber="69">
Mesosoma in lateral view stout, somewhat longer than high, polished. Mesoscutal dimple before prescutellar furrow. Precoxal suture medially on mesopleuron, crenulate. Propodeum with medio-longitudinal carina and with areolation (areola basalis, etc., 
<figureCitation id="AB939A2B1BB49259D63B1CF9BD7BE9BA" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
<pageBreakToken id="33C1AF95FD42C4F1CB6C47499E08B865" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" start="start">Fig</pageBreakToken>
. 14
</figureCitation>
). Hind femur 4.1 times as long as broad distally (
<figureCitation id="956DCD31E7F7B2E7583BC4E6073E09C6" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia and tarsus equal in length. Hind basitarsus as long as tarsomeres 2-3 combined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A92A8E08A4E8C39DA756DC83FA5BC6A6" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
Fore wing: venation &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="98C05238EEA0EF0329E7EAB5A877A038" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2295865AB9920A495E5C0D8883CA6968" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Synaldis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-form&quot;, i.e. 
<emphasis id="0F119C449106C0FB478A0F693E2932DF" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">2-SR</emphasis>
missing hence first and second submarginal cells confluent; 
<emphasis id="B82EE4E797CBE2BE9D71E38EEC44C1E1" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">r + 3-SR</emphasis>
as long as 
<emphasis id="9AA3C3911114B4B2817BA74D0EAB5B9A" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">SR1</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="355934EF393DFD3AEBF26D1FF8B9F36C" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">CU1a</emphasis>
issuing from middle of outer side of subdiscal cell.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="400C4A1C6717512574473DE422797E4B" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
First tergite (
<figureCitation id="2A54363C889BEA5620759FF91E94D72E" captionStart="Figures 10–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 10 - 16. Synaldis cauca sp. n.: 10 head in dorsal view 11 head in lateral view 12 mandible 13 paraclypeal pit 14 propodeum 15 hind femur 16 tergites 1 - 2." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) 2.8 times as long as broad posteriorly, moderately broadening posteriorly. Pair of keels merging into fine striation; spiracles close beyond middle of tergite. Tergites 2-3 fused and as long as first tergite, together with further tergites polished. Ovipositor sheath as long as mid tibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="09F6490443A46DCBC1E11F94D3AF9527" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Scape and pedicel brownish yellow, flagellum darkening brown. Head, mesosoma and first tergite brownish black, rest of metasoma brown. Mandible and mouthparts yellow. Tegula brownish yellow. Legs yellow, hind tarsus greyish fumous. Wings hyaline, pterostigma and veins opaque brownish yellowish.</paragraph>
<caption id="3685AA837C7155899A799150FAFC095B" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11530" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" start="Figures 10–16" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="3F82DE20EE805D7754E943D85815AC43" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis id="4CCF19FB2A64C01AED4CD7EB7ABE5880" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Figures 10-16.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="0B1BFD32FD41D9D0413F73AB98140F17" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2012" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cauca">
<emphasis id="1A87A0A8307C5D5E26BB0F8623C3CCB8" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Synaldis cauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n.: 
<emphasis id="754869D18778AEF648FA641F4BBC7290" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">10</emphasis>
head in dorsal view 
<emphasis id="26BBA3841409B6B01504CD46566D28EC" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">11</emphasis>
head in lateral view 
<emphasis id="A610800F657C2C3A363A809917247CCA" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">12</emphasis>
mandible 
<emphasis id="442C84A6AAD5514282D7F29F4AB303A4" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">13</emphasis>
paraclypeal pit 
<emphasis id="743F9049ABF990D0A81C492EA2665228" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">14</emphasis>
propodeum 
<emphasis id="C7DF3640A1D8C4D535B281E29C3AFC68" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">15</emphasis>
hind femur 
<emphasis id="5B10D644E0F43694A8B5BE125A5092BF" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">16</emphasis>
tergites 1-2.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="722ED933FD210D54166F6EAC7B93DB54" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" type="male and host">
<paragraph id="89FEBA71558121FC39442FC583C5BFA9" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Male and host</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2072AF3B08169987CC54A0C6355E44A2" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0ACFCE9F24813B7A54CD6B7A5BF86AE4" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="444595E095B334C8B1FEF976EA2E0486" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BE3F866DA2ABDAC80F960C8FFA2D646A" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Colombia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E1DA63BC16960D311FB18C6134614ABE" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="205848A418D30935D48D601B5BF4997B" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="268865197DC8DB3C2C12190745092AD9" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
The new species, 
<taxonomicName id="E86E74DF2D4A6FD5443C11C840CFF629" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2012" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cauca">
<emphasis id="0564B657E1771FD6018E879344F39B1B" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Synaldis cauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is near to 
<taxonomicName id="A0406ED363682DDF3C3CBD8BE5E24478" authorityName="Fischer" authorityYear="1967" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutidens">
<emphasis id="C08644DD428BA6BA638DC779DB3000C7" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Synaldis acutidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fischer as both have a mandible with three spiky teeth, 
<emphasis id="64FB879D9C959A0653A62F2E28DC1C55" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">SR1</emphasis>
more than twice as long as 
<emphasis id="AE39F832E1D33434B8F640ECC3E7C05F" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">r + 3-SR</emphasis>
combined and dark bodies; the two species are distinguished as follows (
<taxonomicName id="FB2CDB9CC7763D1114689C078EE80C62" authorityName="Fischer" authorityYear="1967" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutidens">
<emphasis id="12FCC6B1C8017A0E761206CBECA5B415" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">Synaldis acutidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known by its original description: 
<bibRefCitation id="8141BF58B9BFCB5E5BFAB011618DB81C" author="Fischer, M" journalOrPublisher="Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne" pageId="15" pageNumber="82" pagination="431 - 478" refId="B6" refString="Fischer, M, 1967. Die nearktischen Arten der Gattung Synaldis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Braconidae, Alysiinae). Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne 37 (3): 431 - 478" title="Die nearktischen Arten der Gattung Synaldis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Braconidae, Alysiinae)." volume="37" year="1967">Fischer 1967</bibRefCitation>
: 434):
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="46BD754DD61877FB1D52E9D4565055B3" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
<table id="342EAB40C822EBB58935E775E74427C6" inLine="true" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
<tr id="13A1EBA4290560F89EE59235B4029C6E" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="3" pageNumber="70">
<td id="63B5386B3FCFE8E880123EDAEECB631E" colspan="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" rowspan="1">1(2)</td>
<td id="5061F53C82360718ABFE8686F8ED2E58" colspan="1" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" rowspan="1">
Head in dorsal view 1.5 times as broad as long; eye as long as temple. Propodeum polished and with medio-longitudinal carina, spiracles fairly large. Antenna with 16-18 antennomeres. Hind femur 3.5 times as long as broad 
<pageBreakToken id="326C2943D80747AFCFA3969B827D43F2" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" start="start">distally</pageBreakToken>
(Abb. 2 in 
<bibRefCitation id="CA375A00A521C1E9E4A7FAD821FBA8CD" author="Fischer, M" journalOrPublisher="Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne" pageId="15" pageNumber="82" pagination="431 - 478" refId="B6" refString="Fischer, M, 1967. Die nearktischen Arten der Gattung Synaldis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Braconidae, Alysiinae). Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne 37 (3): 431 - 478" title="Die nearktischen Arten der Gattung Synaldis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Braconidae, Alysiinae)." volume="37" year="1967">Fischer 1967</bibRefCitation>
: 434). First tergite twice as long as broad posteriorly, widening more posteriorly. Lower tooth of mandible of usual size (Abb. 1 l.c in Fischer, 1967). Head and mesosoma black, metasoma brown, first tergite yellow. ♀: 1.7 mm. - U.S.A. (Michigan, Wisconsin)
</td>
<td id="E2D2FA05A11A86FBC72F1BE351E11106" colspan="1" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" rowspan="1">
<taxonomicName id="4DD7203B712E80E2BCDBAB8C104D4457" authorityName="Fischer" authorityYear="1967" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutidens">
<emphasis id="67A90DC4CEBE97F1418C892B1A5F4271" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Synaldis acutidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fischer, 1967
</td>
</tr>
<tr id="105442A204C95B2AC805F377BE724EC7" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">
<td id="64845B6D3210C399B0B77299429AAB08" colspan="1" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" rowspan="1">2(1)</td>
<td id="3AF17A3E693A44B57C33162FE42A9DEB" colspan="1" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" rowspan="1">Head in dorsal view 1.7 times as boad as long; eye almost 2.9 times as long as temple (Fig. 10). Propodeum with medio-longitudinal carina and with areolation, spiracles small (Fig. 14). Antenna with 21 antennomeres. Hind femur 4.1 times as long as broad distally (Fig. 15). First tergite 2.6 times as long as broad, widening less posteriorly (Fig. 16). Lower tooth of mandible somewhat small (Fig. 12). Head, mesosoma and first tergite brownish black, metasoma brown. ♀: 2.6 mm. - Colombia</td>
<td id="16283FA9552ED085A8296499AE310416" colspan="1" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" rowspan="1">
<taxonomicName id="6BB8B8667B547DBBECB05BA5F42BF4C2" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2012" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Synaldis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cauca">
<emphasis id="3FFCA8D69D0228863DEDB5CAA30B7F82" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Synaldis cauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</td>
</tr>
